# migrated from tests/cases/compose.chat (hermetic + isolated, perf-held)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test compose]
!timeout 0
# gen160 (E1): compositional emergence — the analytical half, ratcheted so the
# cooperation of eight independently-evolved subsystems over FRESH vocabulary
# (loyal/hound/companion/bryn, none in any other case) can never silently
# regress. No module was added for this: rule intake, fact intake, deduction,
# contrastive abduction, optimal abduction, self-correction, proof and
# robustness simply compose. See tests/composebench.sh for the scored benchmark.
> every loyal hound is a companion
< Learned rule: companion(X) :- loyal(X), hound(X).
> bryn is a hound
< Learned: hound(bryn).
> is bryn a companion?
< No.
> why isn't bryn a companion?
< bryn is not a companion because I am missing: bryn is a loyal. The rule is loyal and hound -> companion.
> what is the easiest way to make bryn a companion?
< The easiest way is to tell me that bryn is a loyal — 1 missing premise via loyal and hound -> companion.
> bryn is loyal
< Learned: loyal(bryn). Now bryn is a companion after all.
> why is bryn a companion?
< companion(bryn) because loyal(bryn) and hound(bryn).
> how robust is that conclusion?
< My conclusion that bryn is a companion rests on 2 load-bearing facts: hound(bryn), loyal(bryn). Removing any one would overturn it.
